## The Retrofit Principle

Existing objects without constitutional payloads can be 
retrofitted:

- Stamp with constitutional ink
- Apply printed RFID label
- Attach NFC sticker
- Add QR code extension

No modification to the object itself. The payload is 
applied externally. The object remains unchanged.

This means the entire existing physical world can be 
constituted without replacement or redesign. 

Retrofit first. Native integration in new products second.

---

## The Standard

The constitutional payload format is identical to the 
digital constitution protocol — same fields, same structure,
same AI readability. The carrier changes. The payload standard 
does not.

One standard. Physical and digital. Unified.

An AI agent that can read a digital .intro file can read 
a physical constitutional payload with no additional training.
The introduction looks the same regardless of how it arrived.

---

## Hardware Commoditisation

The physical infrastructure for this already exists:
- Magnetic ink: magnetic stripe printing technology, decades old
- RFID: printed at billions of units per year for retail
- NFC: in every consumer smartphone
- QR: universal camera recognition on all devices

The gap is not hardware. The gap is:
1. The payload specification — what constitutional data looks like 
   in a physical carrier format
2. The reader standard — how devices extract and parse the payload
3. The AI integration — how agents consume physical constitutional 
   introductions

All three are software and standards problems, not hardware problems.

---

## Relationship to the Interpretation Layer

The interpretation layer (see companion file) sits between 
the world and AI systems. This concept extends the world 
side of that layer into physical reality.

Digital world → .intro file → interpretation layer → AI
Physical world → constitutional payload → interpretation layer → AI

Same layer. Same standard. World unified.

